## Script

**[0:00 — Slide 1: Title]**

Every quarter, US public companies file thousands of earnings reports. If you're an institution, Bloomberg or AlphaSense will synthesise every release, every earnings call, every guidance change — for twenty-five thousand dollars a year. If you're a retail investor? Yahoo Finance shows you a date on a calendar. That's it. Nothing in between. That's the gap I'm addressing.

**[0:25 — Slide 2: The gap]**

I'm calling it Sift. A mobile app — iOS and Android — that does four things for the self-directed retail investor. Pre-earnings briefings generated by an LLM. Real-time alerts the moment an 8-K filing hits the SEC. Post-call transcript analysis, flagging tone and guidance shifts against prior calls. And a machine-learning classifier predicting beat-or-miss before each release. It maps to template 4.2, the Financial Advisor Bot, in the CM3020 Artificial Intelligence module — framed as a research and education tool, not as financial advice.

**[0:55 — Slide 3: What Sift does → Slides 4 and 5: Related work]**

Four pieces of work shaped this. From the literature: FinBERT — Araci, 2019 — pioneered domain-specific BERT for financial sentiment, but recent comparative work shows GPT-4o with prompt engineering now outperforms it by around ten percent on financial text. The technique works, it's just no longer state of the art. The classic Bernard and Thomas papers on post-earnings announcement drift demonstrate that prices systematically move in the direction of the earnings surprise for weeks after release — which is the economic basis for why a surprise classifier is genuinely useful, not just a curiosity. On the commercial side: AlphaSense delivers institutional-grade earnings synthesis, but starts above a thousand dollars a month — inaccessible to retail. And Earnings Whispers, the closest retail-facing tool, offers a calendar with whisper numbers but no AI synthesis, no transcript analysis, and a dated mobile experience.

**[1:55 — Slide 6: The gap, summarised]**

Pull those together and the pattern is clear. The AI techniques work. The economic phenomenon is real. The institutional product exists. What's missing is the bridge — a mobile-native, AI-augmented earnings tool priced for retail. That's the gap Sift fills, and it's why it sits firmly on the research side of the regulatory line.

**[2:20 — Slide 7: Approach]**

Technically: React Native for the mobile app, Supabase for backend and auth, and Python workers on Modal pulling from SEC EDGAR's free RSS feed, Finnhub's earnings calendar, and licensed transcript APIs. The AI core is the surprise classifier — supervised learning over fifteen years of historical earnings — with an LLM layer generating the human-readable briefings.

**[2:45 — Slide 8: Outcome + close]**

By submission, I'll demonstrate the full pipeline on a curated set of fifty tickers, with backtested evaluation of the classifier and a working mobile UI. The longer goal is to ship Sift as an educational research tool for retail investors who want to think for themselves.

